    "constituents_description": "The most important healing constituents of Senna aciphylla are anthraquinone glycosides including sennoside A, sennoside B, sennoside C, sennoside D which act as a purgative by inducing laxative effect due to their ability to inhibit sodium and chloride absorption in the colon, thereby increasing water and electrolyte secretion and enhancing bowel movement. Emodin, another key constituent, is an anthraquinone derivative that exhibits anti-inflammatory and antibacterial properties, potentially contributing to wound healing and prevention of infection in damaged tissues. Sennoside A is responsible for the highest laxative activity among the glycosides, while sennoside B and C contribute to the overall purgative effect. Sennoside D, with its potent cathartic activity, helps in the treatment of constipation and other gastrointestinal disorders. The laxative properties of Senna aciphylla make it a valuable source for the development of natural remedies for treating constipation and related gastrointestinal issues.",
